<font color="#FF0000">ONE MORE STORY</font><br>
<tt>Sun Oct  5 19:04:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Brothers,<br><br>
Just one more tidbit before I get back to numerous questions you guys asked when this thread was rolling a few days ago.<br><br>
I had told Art that I am positioned in a unique part of the country.  I am next to the biggest Air Cav and Artillery training area in the nation.  On any clear night you can hear the rolling thunder coming across the plains.  If one hits the rock just right you can feel the vibration move through the ridge.  A quick hike to the back yard shows the flashes on the horizon far out into the valley.  It will not be long before you can feel that deep vibration in your chest before you ever really hear it.  I am directly under the Air Cav flyway.  Loaches, Hueys, blackhawks and Apaches pulling hard as they carry their load to the exercise.  Damn the road into the valley will be filled with trucks and troops some nights.<br><br>
A quick run to the PX, there yesterday, and you are in the midst of it.  Tanks, troop carriers, everything.  Air Cav sitting in the fields on the sides of the road waiting on their turn.  Doesn't take much to take you back in time.<br><br>
When Desert Storm Kicked in the road flowed  equipment for days.  Full mobility.  I disappeared to other places to help the fleet get ready.<br><br>
If I had PTSD I would be tripping out all the time.  I still fold all this around me.  My job is more of the same.  I guess this is one reason I never lost my support.  I never left.<br>

<p><code>-- triumph7@worldnet.att.net  (SW) </code><p>


